                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d192">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Conger</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrased.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-10-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 30, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. Hay states that peremptory demand should be made for securing religious
                    liberty and rights and full guaranties in the future for Chinese Christians not
                    technically under our protection, as well as exemplary punishment of those who
                    have wronged them. The existing treaty entitles us to this. Should the Chinese
                    Government be inclined to allow them compensation for their losses and
                    sufferings, it should be accepted as an evidence of desire to make all due
                    reparation, and Mr. Conger is directed to use every endeavor to promote such a
                    result.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
